{"parse":{"title":"The Bookseller (short story)","pageid":45093339,"revid":848287495,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For the British magazine, see <a href=\"/wiki/The_Bookseller_(magazine)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"The Bookseller (magazine)\">The Bookseller (magazine)</a>.</div> \n<p><b>\"The Bookseller\"</b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Short_story\" title=\"Short story\">short story</a> by <a href=\"/wiki/Roald_Dahl\" title=\"Roald Dahl\">Roald Dahl</a>. It was first published in the January 1987 issue of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Playboy\" title=\"Playboy\">Playboy</a></i>. \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Plot_summary\">Plot summary</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Bookseller_(short_story)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Plot summary\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/London\" title=\"London\">London</a> bookseller William Buggage and his assistant, Miss Tottle, have been swindling the widows of prominent men by sending fake invoices for pornographic literature supposedly purchased by their recently deceased husbands. The embarrassed widows pay the bill to avoid a public scandal. Buggage is foiled when one of his intended victims points out that her late husband was actually blind.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Controversy\">Controversy</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Bookseller_(short_story)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Controversy\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Dahl's biographer, <a href=\"/wiki/Jeremy_Treglown\" title=\"Jeremy Treglown\">Jeremy Treglown</a>, states that Dahl took the plot of \"The Bookseller\" from \"Clerical Error\" (also published as \"Foot In It\"), a 1935 short story by <a href=\"/wiki/James_Gould_Cozzens\" title=\"James Gould Cozzens\">James Gould Cozzens</a>. Some readers wrote to <i><a href=\"/wiki/Playboy\" title=\"Playboy\">Playboy</a></i> drawing attention to the apparent <a href=\"/wiki/Plagiarism\" title=\"Plagiarism\">plagiarism</a>, but these letters were not published.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Cozzens's original story had been adapted for television in a 1983 episode of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Tales_of_the_Unexpected_(TV_series)\" title=\"Tales of the Unexpected (TV series)\">Tales of the Unexpected</a></i>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> a series with which Dahl was closely associated.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Bookseller_(short_story)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a href=\"/wiki/Jeremy_Treglown\" title=\"Jeremy Treglown\">Treglown, Jeremy</a> (1994). <i>Roald Dahl: A Biography</i>. New York: Farrar.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Roald+Dahl%3A+A+Biography&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Farrar&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.aulast=Treglown&amp;rft.aufirst=Jeremy&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Bookseller+%28short+story%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0717432\">\"Tales of the Unexpected: Clerical Error (1983)\"</a>. <i>Internet Movie Database</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">18 January</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Internet+Movie+Database&amp;rft.atitle=Tales+of+the+Unexpected%3A+Clerical+Error+%281983%29&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.imdb.com%2Ftitle%2Ftt0717432&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Bookseller+%28short+story%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1239\nCached time: 20180908200649\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.068 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.096 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 154/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 2858/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 92/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1722/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.033/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.79 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   85.565      1 -total\n 55.94%   47.862      1 Template:Reflist\n 41.75%   35.727      1 Template:About\n 37.33%   31.938      1 Template:Cite_book\n  5.87%    5.021      1 Template:Cite_web\n  2.64%    2.257      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:45093339-0!canonical and timestamp 20180908200649 and revision id 848287495\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],